00:26:40,659 --> 00:26:45,164
Well, this looks like the place to be.
Even for me.

241
00:26:45,247 --> 00:26:50,044
Yep. Nothin' like a barbershop
for jawin' your socks off.

242
00:26:50,669 --> 00:26:52,671
Where you from, Anderson?

243
00:26:52,755 --> 00:26:56,217
Thornton, Mississippi, sir.
Just a spit from Tennessee.

244
00:26:56,508 --> 00:27:00,054
Well, then you must know
how we all feel down here.

245
00:27:00,137 --> 00:27:03,724
We don't take to outsiders
tellin' us how to live our lives.

246
00:27:03,807 --> 00:27:06,435
And I'm here to tell ya,
our nigras were happy...

247
00:27:06,518 --> 00:27:10,397
..till those beatnik college kids
came down here stirrin' things up.

248
00:27:10,481 --> 00:27:13,817
Before that, there wasn't
anybody complainin'.

249
00:27:13,901 --> 00:27:16,487
Nobody dared.

250
00:27:17,237 --> 00:27:20,449
We got a real peaceful
community down here, Anderson.

251
00:27:20,532 --> 00:27:25,245
Course, they're just like any other folks,
I reckon, when you push 'em too far.

252
00:27:25,329 --> 00:27:30,209
The way I figure it,
it's like three sticks of old dynamite.

253
00:27:30,292 --> 00:27:35,088
You shake it up... and we're gonna
be scrapin' bodies off the street.

254
00:27:36,173 --> 00:27:40,469
I'm just here to investigate the missing
three kids, ask some questions.

255
00:27:40,552 --> 00:27:42,721
If this all boiled down to gravy,...

256
00:27:42,804 --> 00:27:45,974
..there wouldn't be enough
to cover a chicken-fried steak.

257
00:27:46,058 --> 00:27:53,148
Them kids you're lookin' for? I'd bet you a
shiny new dime they're in Chicago now...

258
00:27:53,231 --> 00:27:58,570
..drinkin' a cold beer and havin' a laugh
about the commotion they stirred up here.

259
00:27:58,653 --> 00:28:00,614
Well, I sure hope so.

260
00:28:00,697 --> 00:28:05,285
You can tell your bosses people got
the wrong idea about the South.

261
00:28:06,328 --> 00:28:08,413
You know what I'm talkin' about.

262
00:28:08,496 --> 00:28:12,083
Everybody runnin' around ragged,
backwards and illiterate,...

263
00:28:12,167 --> 00:28:16,046
..eatin' sowbelly and corn pone
three times a day.

264
00:28:16,129 --> 00:28:20,342
Simple fact is, Anderson,
we got two cultures down here.

265
00:28:20,425 --> 00:28:24,220
White culture and a coloured culture.

266
00:28:24,304 --> 00:28:28,725
That's the way it always has been.
That's the way it always will be.

267
00:28:28,808 --> 00:28:33,438
- The rest of America don't see it that way.
- The rest of America don't mean jack shit.

268
00:28:33,521 --> 00:28:35,857
You in Mississippi now.

269
00:28:36,441 --> 00:28:38,568
Oh, that's for sure!

270
00:28:38,651 --> 00:28:40,862
(baseball on radio)

271
00:28:40,945 --> 00:28:44,657
- What's the score, Mr Barber?
- St Louis on top, five to nothing.

272
00:28:44,741 --> 00:28:47,368
- What inning is it?
- Bottom of the seventh.

273
00:28:47,452 --> 00:28:50,955
- You like baseball, Anderson?
- Yeah, I do. You know,...

274
00:28:52,790 --> 00:28:57,629
..it's the only time when a black man
can wave a stick at a white man...

275
00:28:58,129 --> 00:29:00,423
..and not start a riot.

276
00:29:16,355 --> 00:29:18,316
Sir.

277
00:29:18,399 --> 00:29:21,861
We checked on the plate, sir.
Clayton Townley.

278
00:29:21,944 --> 00:29:25,990
Townley. Grand Wizard of
the White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan.

279
00:29:26,073 --> 00:29:28,951
That's him. And we have a lead on the car.

280
00:29:29,035 --> 00:29:32,788
A Choctaw on the reservation
thinks he knows where it is.

281
00:29:32,872 --> 00:29:34,123
Good.

282
00:29:50,139 --> 00:29:52,766
(woman)
You have an appointment next Tuesday?

283
00:29:52,850 --> 00:29:54,935
I'll see you then. Bye-bye.

284
00:30:21,837 --> 00:30:24,506
Afternoon, ladies.

285
00:30:24,590 --> 00:30:27,259
- Can I help you?
- Well, yes, you can.

286
00:30:27,342 --> 00:30:31,221
I tell you, I just...
I hate the way I look. You know?

287
00:30:31,305 --> 00:30:35,017
What do you think? A permanent wave,
maybe? Or a bleach job?

288
00:30:36,727 --> 00:30:40,814
- That looks good. Was it done in here?
- No. Jackson.

289
00:30:40,898 --> 00:30:46,528
A wig's your only hope, hon. You won't
be able to do much with that cue ball.

290
00:30:48,196 --> 00:30:51,950
If you wanna ask us some questions,
this is where you'll hear it all.

291
00:30:52,034 --> 00:30:54,161
Yeah, matter of fact, I do.

292
00:30:55,120 --> 00:30:58,665
I was wonderin' who that gentleman was
that just drove in over there.

293
00:30:58,749 --> 00:31:03,086
- I know that isn't President Johnson.
- His name's Townley. Clayton Townley.

294
00:31:03,170 --> 00:31:06,923
- Are you one of them FBI gentlemen?
- Yes, ma'am, I am.

295
00:31:07,007 --> 00:31:12,179
Well, I think it's a shame if those two kids
are dead. But I sure hope you find 'em.

296
00:31:12,262 --> 00:31:16,558
Thank you. Actually, three kids are
missin'. There's a coloured kid also.

297
00:31:16,933 --> 00:31:21,396
Do you think your people'd be down here
if it weren't for those two white boys?

298
00:31:21,479 --> 00:31:23,648
- Maybe not, miss.
- Mrs.

299
00:31:23,898 --> 00:31:27,110
Pell. Her old man's Ray Stuckey's deputy.

300
00:31:30,322 --> 00:31:32,407
But I'm single.

301
00:31:51,759 --> 00:31:53,845
Move out of the way.

302
00:31:56,431 --> 00:32:00,476
Move over, boy.
We'll take care of this. It's a local problem.

303
00:32:00,560 --> 00:32:03,604
We'll handle this.
We don't need your damn help.

304
00:32:06,149 --> 00:32:10,611
It ain't right havin' blood on Main Street.
How'd that look on the TV news?

305
00:32:12,488 --> 00:32:14,949
- Get up.
- OK, I got him. I got him.

306
00:32:19,203 --> 00:32:20,830
He's the kid from the diner.

307
00:32:20,913 --> 00:32:24,333
Think twice before you talk to
coloured kids with an audience.

308
00:32:24,417 --> 00:32:27,879
They're sending a message from
the boss in Tupelo, and you know it.

309
00:32:27,962 --> 00:32:30,840
I know it, yes. Clayton Townley,
chief pointy head.

310
00:32:30,923 --> 00:32:34,176
Yeah, that's right. How did you know?

311
00:32:34,260 --> 00:32:36,637
Bureau procedure, Mr Ward.
Try it sometime.

312
00:32:36,721 --> 00:32:38,347
We did.

313
00:32:38,431 --> 00:32:40,933
We found the car the kids were driving.

314
00:33:04,456 --> 00:33:06,542
(dog barks)

315
00:33:21,348 --> 00:33:23,434
Good morning.

316
00:33:32,109 --> 00:33:34,194
Good morning.

317
00:34:54,732 --> 00:34:58,403
Two beer cans, a Coca-Cola bottle,
a green plastic bottle,...

318
00:34:58,486 --> 00:35:04,033
..a badly burned wristwatch stopped
at 12.45, and a set of keys. No bodies.

319
00:35:04,117 --> 00:35:08,538
- I want the area searched. Every inch.
- Yes, sir.

320
00:35:08,621 --> 00:35:11,332
- It's a big swamp.
- Every inch, Mr Bird.

321
00:35:15,420 --> 00:35:17,964
I guess they never left Mississippi.

322
00:35:19,382 --> 00:35:21,884
They're dead. They're dead.

323
00:35:22,969 --> 00:35:24,929
Mr Bird?

324
00:35:25,012 --> 00:35:28,724
- Yes, sir?
- There's a telephone at the truck stop.

325
00:35:28,808 --> 00:35:33,312
Get to it, get on it, and get me
a hundred more men here by morning.

326
00:35:33,855 --> 00:35:35,940
- A hundred?
- A hundred.

327
00:35:36,357 --> 00:35:39,443
- Bureau people, sir?
- I don't care if it's the army!

328
00:35:39,527 --> 00:35:42,780
- I want this entire swamp searched!
- Yes, sir.

329
00:35:45,950 --> 00:35:48,202
Don't do it, Mr Ward.

330
00:35:48,285 --> 00:35:52,206
- You'll just start a war.
- It was a war long before we got here.

331
00:36:38,961 --> 00:36:41,213
(dog barking)

332
00:36:50,597 --> 00:36:53,058
Get the fuck outta here now!

333
00:37:33,765 --> 00:37:35,850
Sir?

334
00:37:36,643 --> 00:37:41,439
The sheriff's alibi is solid. He was playing
poker with his wife's brother and cousins.

335
00:37:41,523 --> 00:37:45,568
- The whole time?
- For three hours. He lost $1 1 .38.

336
00:37:47,195 --> 00:37:51,950
There's something else. We're having
a little trouble with the motel manager.

337
00:37:52,033 --> 00:37:56,454
- What kind of trouble?
- He wants us out. We're bad for business.

338
00:37:56,538 --> 00:37:58,581
Buy it.

339
00:37:58,665 --> 00:38:01,209
- Sorry, sir?
- Buy it!

340
00:38:02,252 --> 00:38:04,170
The motel.

341
00:38:04,254 --> 00:38:06,965
- How high can I go?
- Whatever it takes.

342
00:38:30,738 --> 00:38:33,199
Today in Jessup County, Mississippi,...

343
00:38:33,282 --> 00:38:36,869
..amidst the violence of this week,
the eyes of the nation...

344
00:38:36,953 --> 00:38:40,915
..are fixed on the search
for the missing civil rights workers.

345
00:38:41,249 --> 00:38:46,170
I think it's all a big hoax. But if they
are in that swamp, then they asked for it.

346
00:38:46,254 --> 00:38:52,259
(reporter) Naval reserves have joined FBI
agents in searching for the missing men.

347
00:38:52,343 --> 00:38:57,014
I think they planned it. They're sittin' up in
New York laughin' at us Mississippi folks.

348
00:38:57,098 --> 00:39:02,186
- You think it's a hoax?
- A big hoax. They gonna find nothin'.

349
00:39:02,269 --> 00:39:06,690
Civil rights leaders are optimistic
as to the young men's whereabouts.

350
00:39:06,774 --> 00:39:11,362
But privately there is mounting concern
that they will ever be found alive.

351
00:39:11,445 --> 00:39:14,114
They came lookin' for trouble
and found it.

352
00:39:14,281 --> 00:39:18,661
This is Marek Barlbobi, Network News,
Jessup County, Mississippi.

353
00:39:20,955 --> 00:39:25,542
Tell you what I think they oughta be doin'.
Lookin' up in Canada for them boys,...

354
00:39:25,626 --> 00:39:28,253
..instead of our swamps around here.

355
00:39:28,337 --> 00:39:33,884
I'll tell you somethin' else. I think it's
a stunt dreamed up by NAAC people.

356
00:39:33,967 --> 00:39:36,887
- (reporter) NAAC people?
- NAACP.

357
00:39:36,970 --> 00:39:42,059
Know what it stands for? Niggers,
Alligators, Apes, Coons and Possums.

358
00:39:42,142 --> 00:39:44,853
Tell you what you got.
You got your NAACP.

359
00:39:44,937 --> 00:39:48,732
You got your SNCC. You got your COFO.

360
00:39:48,816 --> 00:39:53,362
You know what all that mess is?
B-u-L-L-S-H-l-T.

361
00:39:53,445 --> 00:39:55,531
You got it?

362
00:39:59,159 --> 00:40:04,790
(boy) One day we won't have to say
"Good morning, sir, Mr Sheriff."

363
00:40:04,873 --> 00:40:09,169
Maybe there'll come a time when
we won't have to say "Mr Stuckey".

364
00:40:09,252 --> 00:40:13,757
One day there'll come a time when
we'll just say "Stuckey" or "Sheriff".

365
00:40:13,840 --> 00:40:18,387
And one day there'll come a time when
the sheriff won't even be a white man.

366
00:40:29,814 --> 00:40:31,608
Hello.

367
00:40:34,945 --> 00:40:37,739
I wonder if I could ask you
a few questions.

368
00:40:37,822 --> 00:40:42,243
I don't suppose you could tell me
what kind of flower these are, could you?

369
00:40:42,327 --> 00:40:45,372
I been seein' 'em
all over the place here and...

370
00:40:46,456 --> 00:40:49,250
Never saw such a darn pretty plant.

371
00:40:50,293 --> 00:40:52,170
They're trumpet-pitchers.

372
00:40:52,253 --> 00:40:54,255
Trumpet-pitchers?

373
00:40:54,589 --> 00:40:57,092
They're beautiful. They really are.

374
00:40:57,342 --> 00:41:00,720
They don't smell so good
but they're pretty.

375
00:41:05,016 --> 00:41:07,101
It's nice talkin' to you.

376
00:41:07,185 --> 00:41:12,190
Sorry about interruptin' your meeting
but we can't get anybody to talk to us.

377
00:41:12,273 --> 00:41:14,400
They zip up, like my momma used to say.

378
00:41:14,484 --> 00:41:19,447
People don't wanna talk to you because
they're afraid it'll get back to the law.

379
00:41:19,530 --> 00:41:22,200
- We are the law.
- Not around here you ain't.

380
00:41:22,992 --> 00:41:29,332
We came to find out what happened to
those boys. They were here to help you.

381
00:41:29,415 --> 00:41:34,253
- It ain't coloured folks you should talk to.
- Who should we talk to?

382
00:41:35,046 --> 00:41:37,131
Come on, Aaron.

383
00:41:38,007 --> 00:41:41,177
You should start with the sheriff's office.

384
00:41:42,637 --> 00:41:45,556
- Why aren't you afraid?
- How come you ain't?

385
00:41:45,640 --> 00:41:47,475
Aaron?

386
00:41:48,517 --> 00:41:51,187
Aaron, come on, son.

387
00:42:03,949 --> 00:42:08,954
Here's the pitch. Swing and a line-drive
base hit. Anotherrun is home.

388
00:42:12,625 --> 00:42:15,920
On to the nextpitch by the ruffled
Bob Gibson. He is upset.

389
00:42:16,003 --> 00:42:18,964
Ron Hunt singled to centre.
Hickman passed third...

390
00:42:19,048 --> 00:42:21,217
..and scored the Mets' second run.

391
00:42:21,300 --> 00:42:23,969
Hunt holds on at fiirst,
and the Mets lead two to one.

392
00:42:24,053 --> 00:42:26,138
(doorbell)

393
00:42:36,482 --> 00:42:40,736
Good evening, Mrs Pell. I'm Agent Ward.
This is Agent Anderson.

394
00:42:40,819 --> 00:42:43,113
We're with the FBl.

395
00:42:43,197 --> 00:42:45,282
Is your husband home?

396
00:42:45,365 --> 00:42:47,868
We'd like to have a word with him.

397
00:42:48,535 --> 00:42:50,621
Y'all come in, then.

398
00:42:57,127 --> 00:43:01,632
It's the FBI gentlemen, Clinton. They
wanna ask you some more questions.

399
00:43:01,715 --> 00:43:04,009
You want me to put
your dinner in the oven?

400
00:43:06,720 --> 00:43:09,222
Leave us alone.

401
00:43:09,306 --> 00:43:11,391
Mind if I take a seat?

402
00:43:15,228 --> 00:43:18,398
What's so goddamn important
you got to bother me at home?

403
00:43:18,482 --> 00:43:23,320
I just wanted to run through once again
your movements on June 21st.

404
00:43:23,403 --> 00:43:25,614
June which?

405
00:43:25,697 --> 00:43:27,783
June 21st.

406
00:43:27,866 --> 00:43:32,829
Deputy, we both know what day we're
talking about, so let's do this civilised.

407
00:43:32,913 --> 00:43:37,375
Then you get back to your ball game
and we can get back to Washington.

408
00:43:47,886 --> 00:43:50,430
Please, don't let me interrupt you.

409
00:43:51,222 --> 00:43:56,728
It's just when you've heard a question
a dozen times, it gets kinda boring.

410
00:43:57,228 --> 00:43:59,522
Yeah, I guess so.

411
00:44:05,904 --> 00:44:09,240
- You don't eat together?
- He works funny hours.

412
00:44:12,285 --> 00:44:14,370
- You think that's odd?
- No.

413
00:44:14,454 --> 00:44:16,873
No, I work funny hours myself.

414
00:44:19,751 --> 00:44:22,879
I eat when I'm hungry.
He eats when he can.

415
00:44:22,962 --> 00:44:26,591
- Can I get you somethin'?
- No, no. Thanks.

416
00:44:26,674 --> 00:44:28,635
This is a nice house.

417
00:44:28,718 --> 00:44:31,971
- How long have you lived here?
- I was born here.

418
00:44:32,055 --> 00:44:35,725
But my father lost the house
in a poker game a long time ago.

419
00:44:37,685 --> 00:44:40,688
We've been payin' rent ever since.

420
00:44:43,483 --> 00:44:46,194
It's a wicked game.

421
00:44:48,696 --> 00:44:50,448
Poker.

422
00:44:51,490 --> 00:44:53,576
Wicked.

423
00:44:53,659 --> 00:44:55,620
(Ward) Mr Anderson?

424
00:44:58,372 --> 00:45:01,125
It's nice talkin' to you. Guess I gotta go.

425
00:45:05,296 --> 00:45:08,215
Them pork chops still any good, honey?
Bring me a beer.

426
00:45:08,299 --> 00:45:10,593
(Anderson) Good night.

427
00:45:11,218 --> 00:45:13,137
Let you get back to your baseball.

428
00:45:13,220 --> 00:45:16,974
They say it's the only game
where a black man can wave a stick...

429
00:45:17,057 --> 00:45:19,143
I know. I already heard that one.

430
00:45:25,149 --> 00:45:28,402
Fifty minutes of his alibi
hinges on his wife.

431
00:45:28,485 --> 00:45:31,780
- You talked to her. What's she like?
- She's a nice lady.

432
00:45:31,864 --> 00:45:35,534
Tell me, Mr Anderson.
How does a woman like that end up with...

433
00:45:35,618 --> 00:45:39,496
With shithead in there? You know
what these small towns are like.

434
00:45:39,580 --> 00:45:44,001
A girl spends all her time in high school
lookin' for the guy she's gonna marry...

435
00:45:44,084 --> 00:45:46,670
..and spends the rest
of her life wonderin' why.

436
00:45:46,754 --> 00:45:49,381
Something's wrong. He's too confident.

437
00:45:49,465 --> 00:45:52,301
- Did you see the wedding photograph?
- No.

438
00:45:52,384 --> 00:45:56,305
His three pals, the ushers,
had their thumbs hooked in their belts...

439
00:45:56,388 --> 00:45:59,183
..with their three fingers pointing down.

440
00:45:59,266 --> 00:46:01,894
So what is that?
Some sort of Masonic thing?

441
00:46:01,977 --> 00:46:04,897
No! KKK.

442
00:46:10,319 --> 00:46:13,405
(Pell) I know you ain't drunk.

443
00:46:13,488 --> 00:46:16,658
- (drunk) I'm not drunk.
- All right. You ain't drunk.

444
00:46:16,742 --> 00:46:20,245
I'm just gonna take you
where you can sleep it off.

445
00:46:20,329 --> 00:46:22,414
All right. Hold up.

446
00:46:25,417 --> 00:46:27,502
Watch your head.

447
00:47:21,556 --> 00:47:26,603
Hi. uh... There was a couple of things
I needed to check with you.

448
00:47:26,686 --> 00:47:31,566
- My husband's not here.
- Actually, it was you I wanted to talk to.

449
00:47:32,275 --> 00:47:34,569
Me?

450
00:47:34,652 --> 00:47:37,155
OK. You'd better come in, then.

451
00:47:41,159 --> 00:47:43,161
Just take a minute.

452
00:47:43,244 --> 00:47:46,372
My boss, he's kind of a pain.
A college kid.

453
00:47:46,456 --> 00:47:50,293
He has to dot all the i's
and cross all the t's.

454
00:47:50,376 --> 00:47:55,882
- What is it you wanted to ask me about?
- It's a time thing we're not so clear about.

455
00:47:55,965 --> 00:47:59,010
Should I put your flowers
in some water while you're here?

456
00:47:59,093 --> 00:48:01,178
Yeah. Actually they're for you.

457
00:48:02,430 --> 00:48:04,807
They're beautiful.

458
00:48:04,890 --> 00:48:07,018
They are pretty, aren't they?

459
00:48:07,101 --> 00:48:10,021
They don't smell so nice
but they're pretty.

460
00:48:10,521 --> 00:48:13,024
Can I get you anything? Some tea?

461
00:48:13,107 --> 00:48:15,192
Yeah. Thanks.

462
00:48:30,457 --> 00:48:33,586
Oh, don't you look at that.
It's a terrible photo.

463
00:48:33,669 --> 00:48:36,171
Oh, I don't know about that.

464
00:48:36,964 --> 00:48:40,509
- Is this recent?
- No. I wish.

465
00:48:40,593 --> 00:48:43,220
Well... this here looks recent to me.

466
00:48:43,304 --> 00:48:45,889
We were married 14 years ago.

467
00:48:45,973 --> 00:48:48,934
